\begin_layout Subsubsection
Next Steps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Regional Collaboration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Efforts to organize and fund a regional project in response to CRB-G continue:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Secretariat of the Pacific Community is hosting a 
\series bold
Subregional Workshop on Coconut Rhinoceros Beetle â€“ Guam Biotype
\series default
 on 18-19 September 2017.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Dr.
 Madoka at the University of Tokyo is launching a project with the goal
 of finding the mechanism by which CRB develop resistance to OrNV.
 A kick-off meeting is being held in Tokyo from at the end of September
 2017.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Foreign Exploration for an Effective Biocontrol Agent for CRB-G
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Activities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In January 2017 Moore, Iriarte and Marshall visited Dumaguete, Negros Island,
 Philippines.
 The objective of this trip was to begin searching for new OrNV isolates
 that could be effective against the CRB-G haplotype.
 Native habitats provide a good opportunity to identify candidate OrNV isolates
 (and other potential biocontrol agents).
 OrNV is known to be widespread across the Philippines, where CRB is considered
 as native, and the CRB-G haplotype has been identified from the Dumaguete
 area.
 We had planned to visit Palau during the same trip.
 But we decided to concentrate our efforts in the Philippines because our
 Hawaiian colleagues had already initiated work with CRB and OrNV in Palau.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CRB tissue samples were obtained from live CRB adults collected using both
 pheromone trapping and hand collection from the Philippines.
 Gross observation and molecular DNA analyses were used to determine the
 OrNV infection status and haplotype of individual specimens.
 The pheromone trapping results were disappointing, with only a single CRB
 adult caught; however, hand collection enabled a number of adults and larvae
 to be collected.
 From the CRB specimens collected in the Philippines, one OrNV infected
 CRB adult was identified.
 This specimen was confirmed to be of the CRB-G haplotype, and OrNV from
 the infected tissue was isolated to prepare inoculum for testing efficacy
 against CRB-G.
 Details of the trip and subsequent analysis and results are detailed in
 the report attached as [
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sec:Appendix-1:-Report"

\end_inset

].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Next Steps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An OrNV isolate extracted from a single CRB-G adult was purified and propagated
 in Dr.
 Marshall's lab at AgResearch, New Zealand.
 A USDA APHIS import permit was applied for and has been issued to allow
 shipment of this OrNV isolate to Guam where it will be tested to evaluate
 its usefulness as a biocontrol agent for CRB-G on Guam.
